			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">State of the Bard<a name="65685"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Oct 5 04 1:34 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I may not be the top bard or even the most knowledgeable bard, but I have played Kelraz since a few weeks before Kunark's release. Regrettably prior I was mislead and played a Ranger -- what was I thinking?! Originally my class was one that was unique, people were stunned with my abilities even back in the Oasis of Marr. Today people are still stunned at some of our abilities, but 70 levels later a lot has changed. Here is my take on where the bard class has gone, and where it is currently lacking. I'll admit this is pretty much motivated to get our class retuned as we've gone from one of the most overpowered classes in the game to one of the most underpowered in a very short period of time and while I'd never expect being top dog again I'd at least like to have something to contribute.
<br />

<br />
<b>Original EQ + Kunark:</b>
<br />
In the first two expansions bards were known as the &quot;jack of all trades and masters of none&quot; but that wasn't exactly the case. It is true that when trying to crowd control from Guk to SolB to Sebilis we never quite matched up with our enchanter counterparts. We couldn't tank nearly as well as a Paladin or Warrior. We couldn't dish the damage out as well as a Monk or Rogue. We simply fell right in the middle -- we could do damage, we could crowd control (though with charm in addition to mez we certainly excelled in some of these places), and we could tank. We didn't even need a cleric to heal us but shamans and druids and even paladins could step up and take care of us. Lastly however, the one thing we did have unique to our class was the group resist songs and ability to pull better than any of the other classes using selos and invis in Veeshan's Peak. 
<br />

<br />
<b>Velious:</b>
<br />
Velious was the true birth of the raid bard, as we now had specialized group abilities such as stacking haste. We would be able to increase the damage output of a group of rogues, increase the damage shield on our tank during a Vindicator run, even crank out a little extra mana in the cleric groups. Velious gave birth to the &quot;debuffing&quot; bard as well with Occlusion of Sound (while we did have the 3 chants prior to Velious, not many bards utilized them for debuffing on the same scale that OoS would later be utilized). Lastly we shined in NToV with our resist songs once again only on a grander scale. 
<br />

<br />
<b>Luclin:</b>
<br />
Some controversial, but beneficial, changes came in the Luclin era. While our group resists potential was decreased, AE songs were added that were slightly-weaker making it so that we could support a raid with a smaller number of bards than before. Overhaste upgrades on the Evaj line were made and our songs now actually sang over the haste cap. Additional trinkets such as Amplification and our weapon proc line were added. Bards were ultimately sitting pretty as we could crowd control some of the new encounters (Emp Ssra's lil posse) and still maintain our prior duties of providing mana and resists.
<br />

<br />
<b>Planes of Power:</b>
<br />
The single most powerful increase, and decrease, in our classes power happened during the Planes of Power expansion. Our tanking abilities plummeted, and charm was no longer as viable an option for crowd control due to the inherent risks involved. While our charming cousins of Enchanters and Druids could solo their entire Bastion of Thunder key we had to sit back and watch them work -- and loot the medals later. However we were blessed with a number of abilities that don't even need definition: Fading Memories, Psalm of Veeshan, Poison/Disease chants, Rizlona's. All of our good songs got upgrades making them great songs, and the new songs added such diversity that the bards became quite the envy of other classes. True, enchanters could still out-CC us. True, we could no longer tank anymore ... but we were still on top. Guilds simply couldn't, and still to this day, raid in the Planes of Power without a handful of bards to keep their mana supplies up, their resists high, and their wizards nuking hard.
<br />

<br />
<b>Legacy of Ykesha, Lost Dungeons:</b>
<br />
Our power never really dipped here, but never really grew. LoY gave us the ability to cure poison and disease, an ability we were supposed to have but never really panned out well back in the original EQ release. Lost Dungeons gave us an upgrade to Rizlonas that had us amplify DOTs as well as DDs, but truthfully the damage added compared to the damage added when we first got Rizlonas isn't nearly as noticeable.
<br />

<br />
<b>Gates of Discord:</b>
<br />
The beginning of the end I fear, in GoD we lost our ability to pull as most monsters in the Ikkinz and Uqua and higher end zones now see invis and a monk is far better at splitting them (not that I mind). AE mana has become less of a tool and more of a death trap as on every incoming a bard or two takes the plunge. Our songs became carbon copies with a little upgrade as the songs prior, and the new song is not very high up on the usefulness chart. Some guilds now report benching classes such as Bards and Rangers because the Planes of Power requirement of 72 now leaves 18 people outside and bards and rangers pale compared to monks in damage and usefulness to the guild in various events (Uqua, Ikkinz, etc.)
<br />

<br />
<b>Omens of War:</b>
<br />
And then it happens. We gain 5 levels and seem to go nowhere in potential while all the other classes race by us. We gained a few useful AAs, but not many. Our epic has a effect that has a lot of potential -- but so do all the epics. The main problem I see is the direction raiding is going (thus not making room for all classes to add something) as well as our newest song lineup. For the sake of argument we'll base all numbers on a 2.2 mod (say you have the new epic 1.5 or elemental+ gear) with all the applicable AAs and a VotS.
<br />

<br />
<u>Luvwen's Aria of Serenity(66): </u> While a 5 max level upgrade on Silent Song of Quellious(61) regarding &quot;Reaction Radius&quot; this song is missing the &quot;Frenzy Radius&quot; component thus making it not nearly as useful as Silent Song of Quellious in a number of situations. 
<br />

<br />
<u>Vulka's Chant of Disease(66):</u> These songs are an upgrade in damage (kinda), increasing the DOT by 21/tic (29 with best drum) but the debuff remains the exact same. Actually prior to level 70 you get a more powerful debuff from the old chants than you would with the new ones.
<br />

<br />
<u>Bellow of Chaos(66):</u> A 61 point increase in our DD over a song we got 5 levels and 3 expansions prior. 71 with Puretone or a better than 2.2 mod item or with Shadowsong cloak. 
<br />

<br />
<u>Zuriki's Song of Shenanigans(67):</u> A slight upgrade to Melody of Mischief by 30/tic but the Slow % is the same and half of the time the DOT won't land anyway - even when AEing something static such as the entrance to Phase 5 in the Plane of Time. 
<br />

<br />
<u>Vulka's Chant of Frost(67):</u> see Chant of Disease
<br />

<br />
<u>Luvwen's Lullaby(67):</u> Technically an upgrade to Dreams of Thule I imagine with far worse planning. In Planes of Power, most people had a struggle to get their level 64 mez (Dreams of Terris) so it made sense to have 3 different mezzes (1 ethereal, 1 spectral, and 1 rune). The push and pull were noted a nuisance, as to why the level 65 mez was so nice. Now rather it seems that’s a feature with this new under thought song. This also features half the casting range as the level 65 mez most are familiar with using making this a slight upgrade, a slight downgrade.
<br />

<br />
<u>Cantata of Life(67):</u> As a 3 mana and 15 hp/tic (21 hp/tic with the best lute) increase to Wind of Marr this is the first song that almost seems reasonably thought out.
<br />

<br />
<u>Vulka's Chant of Poison(68):</u> see Chant of Disease
<br />

<br />
<u>War March of Muram(68):</u> Could be considered a massive upgrade to War March of the Mastrug if most players weren't always capped with strength. An 83 point Strength increase (141 with the best Horn), 33 Attack (46), 25 DS (29) is only a slight upgrade over Mastrug, but not as bad as most other songs in our lineup.
<br />

<br />
<u>Yelhun's Mystic Call(68):</u> Like so many of our other songs, simply increasing the max level makes it an &quot;upgrade&quot; though in reality compared to Echo of the Trusik (25% compared to 15% and no loss of DOT focus). Even keeping the lack of DOT component aside, this song is in fact weaker than Echo of the Trusik for spells of every level other than 70. For level 66 spells it is 7.5% weaker, level 67 it is 5% weaker, level 68 it is 2.5% weaker, level 69 it is the exact same (but still missing DOT component) and at level 70 it is only 2.5% weaker than Echo of Trusik, though still missing its DOT component (thus still being weaker). This is by far the worst &quot;upgrade&quot; which is undeniably weaker in every possible scenario than its level 65 counterpart.
<br />

<br />
<u>Verse of Vesagran(69):</u> This was ALMOST a decent song, but it seems someone with little understanding of the bard class put the recast time on it. If the song had a 8 or 6 recast it could be twisted traditionally however the 15 makes this song impossible to twist plus it doesn't remain for the duration of the recast. 5% spellshield / shielding is something people can find on a single PoTime item - I don't believe a group version of the song lasting the entire duration of a twist is overpowering. If no songs get looked at other than this one, we'd at least walk away with one useful song that is actually one we could utilize in a standard twist. 
<br />

<br />
<u>Chorus of Life(69):</u> see Cantana of Life - same song, AE version
<br />

<br />
<u>Eriki's Psalm of Power(69):</u> This sadly is another form of an &quot;upgrade&quot; where the spell is the exact same as the 65 counterpart (Echo of Trusik) but has a 5 level increase. 
<br />

<br />
<u>Vulka's Chant of Flame(70):</u> see Chant of Disease
<br />

<br />
<u>Vulka's Lullaby(70): </u> Another form of an &quot;upgrade&quot; but simply the level limit increased over Lullaby of Morell - while I can understand that these forms of upgrades for things like Mez and Charm are necessary and beneficial, two mezzes is one too many in my opinion where the level 68 one should have retained the benefits of the level 65 version.
<br />

<br />
<u>Voice of the Vampire(70):</u> Actually this song is a pretty decent upgrade.
<br />

<br />
<u>Ancient: Call of Power(70):</u> An actual legitimate upgrade to the Echo of Trusilk song, this will increase DD and DOT power by 5%.
<br />

<br />
Now, a summary. Basically we were given 17 new songs in the new expansion. Of these 17, two were downgrades: Luvwen's Aria of Serenity and Yelhun's Mystic Call. Then we have 5 songs that are practically worthless due to 2 recent nerfs, chant agro and the AE song nerf: Zuriki's Song of Shenanigans and our 4 new chants. 
<br />

<br />
We were given only one new or unique song, Verse of Vesagran. This song was disappointing for the reasons outlined above, mostly because of the reuse timer. A bard is simply unable to twist this song realistically with a timer of 15.
<br />

<br />
Other songs were simply a disappointing increase in power compared to other classes. Our DOTs +29 damage/tic increase compared to say, the difference between the Shaman Blood of Yoppa(70) and Blood of Saryrn(65) was an increase of 122 damage/tic. Even their weakest upgrade between Breath of Wunshi(67) and Breath of Ultor(64) is 49 damage/tic. Druids have similar increase in their damage output as Wasp Swarm(68) is 116 more damage/tic than its predecessor Swarming Death(63) and their GoD DOT Sylvan Embers(65) gets a 38 damage/tic increase with Immolation of the Sun(67), a 52 damage/tic increase over their PoP DOT Immolation of Ro(62). Lets not forget that these values are unmodded, where all the bard data included is modded plus we can't use regular spell foci that all other casters can.
<br />

<br />
More disappointment comes with our upgraded buffs, such as War March of Muram which simply is a copy/paste increase. While the increase levels are on par with other classes, the enchanters also get a +20 chance to critical on their haste and the shaman get a 85 point str/dex stat increase over the cap on their focus. 
<br />

<br />
Some songs are acceptable upgrades in my eyes. Cantata of Life and Chorus of Life have similar increases as their Druid and Enchanter counterparts Oaken Vigor (+20 hp/tic increase) and Voice of Quellious (+2 mana/tic increase). Vulka's Lullaby, Voice of the Vampire, and Ancient: Call of Power one can't really ask for much more than what we got on these. Even Bellow of Chaos was an acceptable increase in damage. However an expansion isn't made up around 5 &quot;acceptable&quot; songs and 1 song that is new, decent, but not designed with the end user in mind. Our songs ultimately need some serious work. Improving (fixing) Puretone and giving bards the ability to use certain foci will help to get the songs in line. Removing the instrument caps would help even more. However ultimately there is a lot of work to be done. 
<br />

<br />
My suggestions would start with fixing Verse of Vesagran, then add something to the OoW Rizlona line to make them legitimate upgrades on their GoD predecessors. Then there's still a lot of songs left to be fixed or re-tuned but at least it'd be a start. Frankly, its disappointing how little thought went into these songs when on the EQLive boards we were told by Ashlanne over at <a target="_new" href="http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=bardbalance&amp;message.id=1416  ">http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=bardbalance&amp;message.id=1416  </a> that they were works in progress and would get updated in the future - but didn't. 
<br />

<br />
Prior to OoW I was very happy with my class. I'll admit that the total worthlessness of any wind mod over 1.8 (Shroud of Provocation worthless?) is frustrating. There were definitely a few bugs with the class, though I always felt strongly that our class was fine just the way we were. If you don't believe me, check out these threads to prove my one-sidedness to the whole issue: <a target="_new" href="http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallfrm14.showMessage?topicID=8.topic">http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallfrm14.showMessage?topicID=8.topic</a>, <a target="_new" href="http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallfrm14.showMessage?topicID=2.topic">http://p201.ezboard.com/ftheconcerthallfrm14.showMessage?topicID=2.topic</a>. I had no problem being a SOE fan boy, because the class was well off. Today, I'm amazingly frustrated and if nothing else my in-game attendance is a testament to that.
<br />

<br />
If the developers really have trouble coming up with ideas, Keiz's post here: <a target="_new" href="http://eqdiva.com/Forums/ShowPost.aspx?PostID=63706">http://eqdiva.com/Forums/ShowPost.aspx?PostID=63706</a> is a good place to start. h*ll even personally I can think of a few - a resist chorus type song (as weak as the AE songs) for all 5 resist types. A single resist type (FR, CR, PR, MR, DR) AE song that increases your resist in that area as powerful as PoVeeshan would have. A group disease or poison or curse cure song. I'd never want my class to be overpowered, but certainly don't want them underpowered like they are and like they are going to be either. 
<br />

<br />
So to you, member of this Bard community, what can we do? I'm getting to be as frustrated as most of the other higher end bards and ready to switch over to a cleric or maybe another game -- and that’s saying a lot since I've played Kelraz for the past few years exclusively in one of my server's top raiding guilds.
<br />
</span></td>
